00:29:30.910 --> 00:29:34.470
So we very often provide
designers,

00:29:34.470 --> 00:29:35.540
developers with feedback.

00:29:35.540 --> 00:29:37.040
They give us PDFs.

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:39.150
We provide them with
feedback back.

00:29:39.150 --> 00:29:42.230
So some of the tools that
we use are Google Drive,

00:29:42.230 --> 00:29:49.330
specifically the Docs editor
as well as the PDF viewer.

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:55.510
PDF editor is like Preview on
Mac or Acrobat, and Skitch.

00:29:55.510 --> 00:29:59.080
And so I'll briefly mention for
PDF editors, it's really,

00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:02.520
really, really useful to be able
to just load up a set of

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:04.270
screenshots and just annotate.

00:30:04.270 --> 00:30:06.070
PDFs have this awesome
annotation feature where you

00:30:06.070 --> 00:30:09.860
can just drop in a text
bubble annotation.

00:30:09.860 --> 00:30:11.900
And you can just really quickly
mark up all the

00:30:11.900 --> 00:30:14.000
different things that you either
see wrong or you like

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:14.700
or whatever.

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:18.890
It's a good way for both
developers or product managers

00:30:18.890 --> 00:30:21.530
to communicate with designers,
as well as for designers to

00:30:21.530 --> 00:30:23.560
communicate to developers.

00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:26.790
So designers, rather than using
specs or red lines if

00:30:26.790 --> 00:30:29.930
you don't want to, you could
just create your mockups,

00:30:29.930 --> 00:30:32.230
throw them into a PDF, and then
just annotate like, this

00:30:32.230 --> 00:30:33.050
should stretch.

00:30:33.050 --> 00:30:37.210
This should be whatever,
something else.

00:30:37.210 --> 00:30:39.190
You could use PDF editors
or PDF annotations.

00:30:39.190 --> 00:30:41.920
ADAM KOCH: We use this is a
feedback mechanism a lot.

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:44.610
It's worth noting, though,
that not all PDF viewer

00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:47.790
support adding these
annotations, but a lot do.

00:30:47.790 --> 00:30:50.600
So if you're looking for it in
your particular PDF viewer,

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:52.110
you may need to switch
to another one if

00:30:52.110 --> 00:30:55.160
you can't find it.

00:30:55.160 --> 00:30:57.140
ROMAN NURIK: Then for Google
Drive, one of the things I

00:30:57.140 --> 00:30:59.480
love about Google Drive is
its commenting abilities.

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:04.000
So in Docs, you can just spawn a
comment thread on a specific

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:05.780
line of feedback.

00:31:05.780 --> 00:31:08.790
And then in the image editor
or the image viewer are as

00:31:08.790 --> 00:31:12.160
well as the PDF preview, I
believe there's a way to

00:31:12.160 --> 00:31:15.990
highlight a certain portion and
start a comment thread on

00:31:15.990 --> 00:31:18.140
a single rectangle.

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:20.460
So it's similar to the PDF
editor in the sense that you

00:31:20.460 --> 00:31:22.470
can annotate things.

00:31:22.470 --> 00:31:26.530
But certainly the combination of
these tools we found to be

00:31:26.530 --> 00:31:27.135
super useful.

00:31:27.135 --> 00:31:28.500
ADAM KOCH: It's nice when
there's a lot of back and

00:31:28.500 --> 00:31:30.290
forth, when you've got a few
people commenting on a

00:31:30.290 --> 00:31:32.870
particular issue.

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:34.440
ROMAN NURIK: And the last
one, I'd say, Skitch.

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:37.820
So Skitch is something that
basically lets you annotate

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:39.340
screenshots.

00:31:39.340 --> 00:31:42.860
And it's really useful for
feedback on specific photos or

00:31:42.860 --> 00:31:44.010
specific mockups.

00:31:44.010 --> 00:31:49.160
It doesn't easily let you work
with multiple things at once,

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:51.740
multiple screenshots at once,
as far as I know.

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:54.660
But it's certainly very useful
for creating arrows and

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:58.090
annotations and things like that
on top of your mockups.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:31:59.790
So these are just some
of the tools we use.

